Your current `UserSession` already has the token-expiry fields:

```java
private Instant accessTokenExpiresAt;
private Instant refreshTokenExpiresAt;
```

What is missing is only Arthur’s own session expiry:

```java
private Instant sessionExpiresAt;
```

Add it near `sessionId`:

```java
private String sessionId;
private Instant sessionExpiresAt;
private String appId;
```

Then populate all three values when creating the session in `AuthService.handleCallback(...)`.

```java
Instant now = Instant.now();

session.setSessionId(UUID.randomUUID().toString());

session.setSessionExpiresAt(
        now.plusMinutes(
                arthurSecurityProperties.getSession().getTtlMinutes()
        )
);

Object expiresIn = tokenResponse.get("expires_in");
if (expiresIn instanceof Number value) {
    session.setAccessTokenExpiresAt(
            now.plusSeconds(value.longValue())
    );
}

Object refreshExpiresIn = tokenResponse.get("refresh_expires_in");
if (refreshExpiresIn instanceof Number value) {
    session.setRefreshTokenExpiresAt(
            now.plusSeconds(value.longValue())
    );
}
```

Use this import if needed:

```java
import java.time.Instant;
import java.util.UUID;
```

Then in `HandoffService.exchange(...)`:

```java
response.setSessionExpiresAt(session.getSessionExpiresAt());
response.setTokenExpiresAt(session.getAccessTokenExpiresAt());
```

Important:

* `accessTokenExpiresAt` should come from Ping’s standard `expires_in` token-response field.
* `refreshTokenExpiresAt` may remain `null` with PingFederate unless they return a refresh-expiry field or provide it in their token policy.
* `sessionExpiresAt` is owned by Arthur and should match the Redis session TTL.
